WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:30.749
Welcome to Grade 1 English, Unit 1: Welcome to School. In this first unit, your child learns the words for things in the classroom, some colours, and how to say their own name and age. They meet the idea that school is a happy, welcoming place. The goal is warm, confident first steps in English — not perfect spelling. In this short lecture, preview the key ideas and prepare for the independent lesson.

2
00:00:30.829 --> 00:00:53.976
By the end of this unit, you will be able to name common classroom objects (table, chair, book, pencil…). you will also name and point to colours (red, blue, green, yellow…). you will also say “my name is ___. i am ___ years old. i like ___.”. Keep these goals in mind as you work.

3
00:00:54.056 --> 00:01:10.024
Your vocabulary work begins with these words: table, chair, whiteboard, ABC chart, clock, book. Listen to each pronunciation in the vocabulary lab, study its meaning in context, and use the word accurately in your own discussion and writing.

4
00:01:10.104 --> 00:01:24.383
The reading sequence includes Amal's First Day and Talk about Welcome to School. Read actively. Identify each text's central ideas, notice viewpoint and reliability, and support every inference with relevant evidence from the text.

5
00:01:24.463 --> 00:01:41.697
The first language focus is Language pattern 1. Listen to the model, point to the matching picture, then say the pattern: This is a ___. Notice the structure in the model examples, then apply it deliberately in connected sentences and paragraphs.

6
00:01:41.777 --> 00:01:57.745
In speaking, you will complete Speaking 1 - Listen and point. Organise your ideas, use evidence and respond clearly to questions. In writing, you will plan, draft, check and revise. Use the success criteria before submitting your work.

7
00:01:57.825 --> 00:02:15.060
You are ready to begin. Start with the vocabulary lab, continue through reading and comprehension, apply the grammar focus, and complete the speaking and writing practices. Use AI English for hints and feedback, and bring your questions to the live sessions.
